        <active>false</active>
        <article><![CDATA[<p>If you have the Tanium <a title="Threat Response" href="https://docs.tanium.com/threat_response/threat_response/index.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow">Threat Response</a> module licensed, imported, and configured in your Tanium environment, then you&#39;ll want to configure these settings to enable quarantining of endpoints via API.<br />If you <em>don&#39;t </em>have Tanium Threat Response installed then you can skip this step, as you won&#39;t be able to quarantine endpoints in your environment. </p>
<p>As per the <a href="https://docs.tanium.com/threat_response/threat_response/isolating_endpoints.html?#testquarantine" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow">Tanium documentation</a> around quarantining/isolating endpoints in your network: in order to quarantine an endpoint, you should create custom Action packages from the existing out-of-box quarantine packages, and configure the &#34;<em>taniumquarantine.dat</em>&#34; file that&#39;s associated with <em>each quarantine package</em> (for Windows, Linux, and Mac) in your Tanium environment. <br />If you haven&#39;t done that, please follow along with the documentation (or contact your Tanium account manager) and then come back here to complete this step. </p>]]></article>
